.SH NAME
.\" --------------------------------------------------------------------
time \- Displays or sets the system time
.
.
.
.\" --------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH SYNOPSIS
.\" --------------------------------------------------------------------
.
.SY time
.OP /?
.YS
.
.SY time
.OP /t
.YS
.
.SY time
.RI [ new_time ]
.YS
.
.
.
.\" --------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH DESCRIPTION
.\" --------------------------------------------------------------------
.
Type TIME with no parameters to display the current time setting and a prompt
for a new one.  Press ENTER to keep the same time.

If Command Extensions are enabled the TIME command supports
the /T switch which tells the command to just output the
current time, without prompting for a new time.
.
.
.\" --------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH OPTIONS
.\" --------------------------------------------------------------------
.
.TP
.B /?
Display help and exit. Other options are ignored.
.
.TP
.B /t
Displays the current time without prompting you for a new time.
.
.TP
.I new_time
.
Sets the system time to the new time specified in format
.IR HH [ :MM [ :SS [ .NN ]]]
.RB [ am | pm ]
, where
.I HH
is in hours (required),
.I MM
is in minutes, and
.I SS
is in seconds.
.I NN
can be used to specify hundredths of a second. If
.B am
or
.B pm
is not specified, time uses the 24-hour format by default.
.
.
.\" --------------------------------------------------------------------
